post_text:
Parents,

As we approach next week we want you to realize that the entire staff is back and working hard to ensure we are prepared to welcome our students, your children, into our buildings. We understand that there are many questions left unanswered and we are preparing a document to go out tomorrow further explaining:

1) Hybrid Opening (A/B Day expectations, Week 1 Expectations)
2) Remote Learning Options in the High School
3) NTCC After School Options

As a reminder, NTCC starts tomorrow, students need to arrive to the school by 8am in order to catch the bus.

Please contact Mr. Holmes in the High School with any questions.

post_text:
Attention All NTCC Students and Parents
Please be advised that NTCC will be starting August 27, 2020. The Northeast Bradford School District will not start school until August 31, 2020. We will be providing a bus from the district to NTCC on August 27th and August 28th. You will need transportation to NEB these mornings. The bus will depart NEB to NTCC at 8:10 promptly. The bus will return students to NEB from NTCC after the completion of the day. Students will need a ride home from NEB at that time. Any issues please contact Mr. Holmes at 570-744-2521 ext 2210.

Dear Parents and Students,

Given the challenges we are currently facing we have decided to cancel summer band camp. We understand that this may be upsetting to many students and we apologize for any inconvenience. Please know that we are making decisions based on what we feel is in the best interest of the students, staff, and community. Also know that we are committed to our music department and our band front and we will resume activities as soon as we feel we are able. If you have any concerns please feel free to contact me.

Matthew Holmes, High School Principal

NORTHEAST BRADFORD SCHOOL BOARD VACANCY

Community Members - Northeast Bradford Board of Education is seeking to fill the vacancy of the school director. The length of the term will be until December 2021, at which time if the appointed member wishes to remain, they must run for election in 2021, to fill a 2-year term. Candidates must not be an employee of the District

Interested applicants, please visit our website for eligibility requirements and how to apply.

APPLICATION DEADLINE: July 6, 2020 - 3:00 PM

Dear Families,

We will be collecting technology, library books, and any remaining box tops on June 2nd and 3rd. Times of drop off will be from 8 am until 2 pm. If another time needs to be requested, please contact your child’s school.

At the elementary school, parents may pick up their student’s final report cards and any personal items that were left at the school.

All technology for all grade levels may be turned in to either school. Please remember to bring all devices loaned and their appropriate charging cord.

At the elementary school, parents will drive through the bus circle, and at the high school, parents should drop off in the front of the high school building. Please remain in your vehicle, and a school staff member will come to you.

post_text:
CONGRATULATIONS to the following 6th graders who worked hard and completed a series of "challenges" for Mrs. Funk!

The students were given a list of 20 challenges to pick from and they could decide how many they wanted to complete over the course of four weeks. Each "challenge" had its own set of criteria and was broken into various categories including designing, building, transforming, writing, or illustrating. Students then uploaded their work and shared it via email.
Kudos to all who took on the challenge!

Mason Alexander, Leah Beebe, Hunter Comstock, Leah Fries, Russell Martin, and Tyler Thoman

We will share more specific information with our seniors as we approach June 6, 2020, but we wanted to share this information with you now for your planning purposes.

post_text:
A Message from the School Nurse:

Dear Parents or Guardians,

Hope this letter finds you all safe and healthy. With summer fast approaching, now is a great time to schedule your child’s physical for the next school year. Pennsylvania requires that students in kindergarten, grade 6, and grade 11 have a physical exam. THIS IS ALSO A GREAT TIME FOR STUDENTS TO HAVE THEIR IMMUNIZATIONS UPDATED.

Before entering 7th grade: Tdap & MCV
Before entering 12th grade: MCV#2

Please have your family provider complete the attached form and return it to the school health office. Any questions, contact me at jgross@nebpanthers.com.

To download the Physical Exam form, please visit our webpage.

Kindergarten Registration Update:

In lieu of the originally planned registration process, we have posted an online form for parents of students who will need to enroll in Kindergarten for the 2020-2021 school year. If you have a student who will be of school age to begin Kindergarten this Fall please check out the link available on our school district's website. Additional details about finalizing your child's enrollment and potential screening dates will be forthcoming. If you cannot fill out the form online, please leave a voicemail at 570-744-2521 x2265, and we will set up an alternative option.

The Northeast Bradford SD is pleased to announce that we have been able to install a few access points throughout our community that will allow students connectivity near their homes. These access points are located at the Warren Center Community Hall, Orwell Community Hall, Rome Fire Company Hall, LeRaysville Fire Hall, and the Northeast Bradford High School. Students may also access Wi-fi at the Rome Presbyterian Church by contacting Pastor Karen Ballard.

Please remember to follow all social distancing guidelines as you access the Wi-Fi at these locations.

Buses will begin their routes at the district and depart at 10 AM. Buses will be following their afternoon bus routes. Dear Parents and Community Members:

Good evening, Governor Wolf and The Pennsylvania Department of Health has issued a statement that all K-12 schools immediately close as a precautionary measure against transmission of the coronavirus. The school will remain closed from March 16 through March 27. The district will be working with the department of education regarding the required 180 days of school.

The closures affect all programming at the school, including before and after-school activities, all athletic and extracurricular practices and competition and weekend events including community activities.

We will keep you informed if circumstances change as we work together to continue to provide a safe and healthy environment for our students.

post_text: 6th graders conducted an experiment called the Mayflower Challenge. Each team was given the same set of supplies: 3 sheets of paper and 3 paper clips. Their task was to design a boat that would float and hold the most "Pilgrims" (10 cm blocks). Out of 15 boats, only two sank! The winning boat, designed by Ben Ellis, Hailey Heeman and Xavier Pierce, held 366 blocks.

Junior high girls basketball 7th grade team remains undefeated (8-0) on the season picking up 3 wins this week! The 8th grade team also went 3-0 this week and are sitting at 7–1 on the season. post_text:
Mrs. Keeney’s 6th grade students created a display related to the story “Hatchet,” which is about a 13-year-old boy who is stranded in Canadian forest following a plane crash. Brian is alone in the forest with nothing but the clothes on his back and a hatchet his mother gave him before the trip.

The students were tasked with drawing a blueprint of their shelter and making their drawing come to life with limited supplies.

Dear Parents and Guardians:

The Northeast Bradford School District will host The Vara Group, along with Pennsylvania State Police and The Children’s House for a special presentation on Community-based Detection and Prevention of Human Trafficking and how young people, schools and parents can intervene.

This presentation will be given to students in grades 5-12 on Monday, Nov. 25, with a special evening presentation for parents on Wednesday, Dec. 4. If you do not want your child to attend this presentation, please notify the school in writing.

post_text:
NEB is planning its 34th annual Hands Across Northeast fundraiser to help deserving families during the holidays. Students, staff and community members are invited to donate money towards the purchase of food, clothing and toys as gifts for families in our district. Send donations to the elementary school office or to a student’s teacher. (Make checks payable to NEB Elementary School.)

For each donation received, a decoration will be added to the elementary school halls as a reminder of the spirit of giving.

The fundraising activity will culminate on Dec. 19 at 2 pm – when elementary school students and staff assemble in the front of the building to join hands in a circle and sing Christmas carols to commemorate this special time of year. Community members are welcome to take part.

Hey basketball fans! Check out the NEB junior high teams.....last week both the girls 7th and 8th grade teams went 3-0, picking up wins over Wyalusing, North Penn Liberty and Towanda! post_text: Panther Volleyball team makes NEB history!
shared_text:
NEB Athletics
November 1, 2019 at 12:53 PM ·

Congratulations to our Panther Volleyball team as they finished their season in the District 4 finals last night. Our girls had to settle for 2nd place(not too shabby!!) but a little NEB Volleyball history - this was the first EVER NEB Volleyball team to make it to the District finals!!!! Way to make history girls!! We are proud of all off you and look forward to years of exciting matches!!

post_text: On Nov. 1, students and families gathered in front of the Bradford County Courthouse to honor the winners of the 8th annual Bradford County Republican Women Essay Contest. Congratulations to NEB's Leah Fries, 6th grader, who won 1st place in the 4th, 5th, 6th grade category. About 250 students countywide submitted essays and six students were selected for 1st and 2nd place prizes. Leah received an engraved plaque and $75. The contestants had the opportunity to read their winning essays to the crowd.
